6.28	We recommended that Management to:
require the Municipal Engineer to provide a complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects pursuant to Item V of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
direct the Municipal Assessor to assist the Municipal Engineer in the assessment of the fair market value of the road lot component of all existing local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality;
direct the Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain an LRIRRM and conduct reconciliation with the Municipal Accountant between the list of inventory per LRIRRM with those recorded in the RPI; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to take-up the necessary correcting/adjusting entries to recognize completed road projects from previous years and provide appropriate depreciation relative thereto.

7.21	We recommended that Management require the:
Municipal Accountant to (1) draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) taking up the (i) record the costs of the ongoing infrastructure projects based on actual accomplishments; and (ii) reclassification of the assets acquired for distribution and small tangible items to the appropriate inventory/expense accounts;
Acting-General Service Officer to report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) duly signed by the Head of Accounting Unit, Inspector/Appraisal Committee and approved by Head of Agency or authorized representative, and submit the report to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition;
Inventory Committee to (i) conduct a complete physical count of PPE; and (ii) prepare/submit the corresponding RPCPPE (with appropriate remarks on the condition and whereabouts of the PPE) to the Accounting, GSO, and COA; and
Concerned officials and committees to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE Accounts Balances of the Municipality in compliance with COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

10.24	We recommended that Management:
practice bulk procurement in order to avail the most advantageous prices that the suppliers can offer;
instruct the BAC to strictly adhere to the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184 and R.A. No. 9502 also known as the Universally Accessible Cheaper and Quality Medicines Act of 2008 and Rule No. 36 of its IRR to ascertain that the procured drugs and medicines are of good quality, essential to the people and within the PNDF;
BAC including its Secretariat/Technical Working Group (TWG) to (i) consider/distinguish VAT-exempt items from those usually subject to 12% VAT in the determination of ABC and in the preparation of bid documents; and (ii) undertake detailed evaluation of financial component of bids to ensure that individual cost estimates submitted by participating bidders are in compliance with the pertinent laws, rules, and regulations; and
Acting-GSO to ensure that VAT-exempt transactions are itemize/shown separately in sales invoice.

12.30	We recommended that Management:
promptly implement PPAs finance by subject-fund that socio-economic benefits expected to produce by these projects will be enjoyed by constituents within the budget year and ensure continued economic development in the community;
instruct the BAC, together with its Technical Working Group and Secretariat to (a) strictly comply with the use of the latest approved PBDs and standard forms; and (b) henceforth, be diligent in the conduct of eligibility screening, bid evaluation, and post-qualification such that documents submitted by the bidders are scrutinized thoroughly to ensure their authenticity, veracity, and completeness as the basis for the evaluation of the most advantageous and reasonable bids to ensure that contracts are awarded/transacted only to eligible supplier/bidder;
assess the proper disposition of the contracts for those projects that the implementation and completion were being hampered by delays incurred by the Contractor;
advise the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the OIC-Municipal Engineer and BAC Secretariat, to verify all supporting documents as to the completeness and see to it that the same is attached to the disbursement vouchers before payments are made to establish the legality and proper accountability over financial transactions; and
direct the Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the contractors to comply with the required posting of information and publicity on programs/projects/activities of government agencies and to inform the audit team within ten (10) days after the award of the project or before the start of the program/project/activity that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted at the project site as stated in COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to undertake the following courses of action:

instruct the OIC-HRMO to (i) submit the DTRs or any other means of recording attendance; order authorizing the employees to physically report for work; and duly validated accomplishment reports of the concerned officials and employees, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant in accordance with CSC Memorandum Circular No. 21, Series of 1991 and COA Circular No 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 to validate all the payments made; and (ii) monitor and scrutinize logbook entries to arrive at the correct man-hour/attendance actually rendered to avoid overpayment or underpayment of claims;

require the SB Secretary or the person responsible to submit the minutes of sessions and/or entries of attendance in the logbook during the implementation of ECQ to substantiate COVID-19 HP given to SB Members;

instruct the OIC-HRMO and the Municipal Accountant to submit written explanation why some officials and employees were able to claim more or less than the allowed COVID-19 HP per DTR;

advise the Municipal Accountant to verify and cross-check all data relating to payroll of employees with the approved DTRs and accomplishment reports; 

direct the head of each department having jurisdiction of the subject employees to ensure the correctness of information disclosed in the DTRs and accomplishment reports before approving the same; and

advise the 32 employees to refund excess claims totaling ₱29,300.00.

We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following courses of action:

Abide strictly with the project schedule to ensure the full implementation of all the priority projects targeted during the year for the benefit of the Municipality and the constituents in general; 



Assign the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to undertake close monitoring of activities and the implementation thereof in accordance with the AIP/Development Plan; 



Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to set early schedule for the conduct of procurement proceedings to ensure timely implementation of PPAs;



Organize an Inspectorate/ Evaluation Committee which will evaluate gaps and differences between the plan and actual accomplishments and recommend corrective actions; and

Give priority on high impact projects and refrain from using the 20% Development Fund for soft projects which do not partake the nature of capital expenditures or investments.

We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following courses of action:

Require the MPDC and the Designated Solid Waste Management Officer to (i) prepare the LGU SWM SCMAR and submit the same to the Regional Office No. III and SWMD-PDTSS every six months to monitor promptly the status of compliance with R.A. No. 9003; and (ii) coordinate closely with the NSWMC to ensure the approval of the Ten-Year Municipal Solid Waste Management Plan (MSWMP);

Pursue the establishment of a functional Sanitary Landfill;



Prioritize the generation of electricity and water supplies in the MRF;



Develop programs and projects on the mitigation of solid wastes in the MRF through re-using, recycling, and composting of wastes;

Instruct the designated Solid Waste Management Officer to (i) strictly enforce the “No Segregation, No Collection Policy”; 



(ii) discontinue the practice of incinerating solid wastes in the MRF; 



(iii) relocate the two shredders to a safe storage/warehouse in the MRF to maximize its use and avoid further damage on the equipment; 



(iv) maximize the use of its MRF Office; 
and 

(v) abide strictly with the project schedule to ensure the full implementation of all the solid waste management priority projects targeted during the year for the benefit of the Municipality and the constituents in general; and

Revisit and propose an amendment to the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) with Econest for the inclusion of the provision on the process of arbitration among the terms and conditions thereof pursuant to Section 59.2 of R.A. No. 9184.

6.7	We recommended and the LCE agreed to undertake the following courses of action:
instruct the OIC-HRMO to (i) submit the DTRs or any other means of recording attendance; order authorizing the employees to physically report for work; and duly validated accomplishment reports of the concerned officials and employees, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant in accordance with CSC Memorandum Circular No. 21, Series of 1991 and COA Circular No 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 to validate all the payments made; and (ii) monitor and scrutinize logbook entries to arrive at the correct man-hour/attendance actually rendered to avoid overpayment or underpayment of claims;
require the SB Secretary or the person responsible to submit the minutes of sessions and/or entries of attendance in the logbook during the implementation of ECQ to substantiate COVID-19 HP given to SB Members;
instruct the OIC-HRMO and the Municipal Accountant to submit written explanation why some officials and employees were able to claim more or less than the allowed COVID-19 HP per DTR;
advise the Municipal Accountant to verify and cross-check all data relating to payroll of employees with the approved DTRs and accomplishment reports;
direct the head of each department having jurisdiction of the subject employees to ensure the correctness of information disclosed in the DTRs and accomplishment reports before approving the same; and
advise the 32 employees to refund excess claims totaling ₱29,300.00.

We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following courses of action: 

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to: (i) transfer the funds from various NGAs and trust collections from the General Fund to the Trust Fund books in accordance with existing accounting policy; 



(ii) remit or return the unutilized PDAF balance to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund of the National Government thru the Bureau of Treasury; and 



(iii) coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for the return of unused funds to the source agencies (SAs) or to the National Treasury, as the case may be; 



Direct the Municipal Treasurer to draw a check for the remittance of unutilized amount of all completed projects and the ante mortem fees to the transferor agencies concerned and to BAI, respectively.



Advise the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and the Municipal Engineer to comply strictly with the policy guidelines and procedures in the implementation of the LGSF-AM Program, particularly the documentary requirements and conditions enumerated under Sections 4.4.1 and 4.4.2(iii) of the JMC.

We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following courses of action:

Exercise prudence and diligence in the disbursement of funds and enforce compliance with the provisions of DBM Budget Circular Nos. 2004-5A and 2007-3 on the use of the local budget for honoraria of members of the BAC, TWG, and BAC Secretariat to prevent excessive and unlawful payments;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to: (i) make sure that savings from the approved local budget were duly approved by the Sanggunian before effecting any payment of honoraria to the members of BAC, TWG, and BAC Secretariat chargeable to the General Fund (GF); 

(ii) treat the collections from the sale of bid documents as receipts in the Trust Fund (TF) books; and 

(iii) ensure that withholding taxes are deducted from the payment of honoraria of BAC Members, TWG, and BAC Secretariat in accordance with BIR Revenue Memorandum Order No. 23-2014 dated June 20, 2014; and

Require the HRMO/personnel in-charge of payroll preparation to provide the computation on the payments of honoraria and submit the required supporting documents to the Municipal Accountant in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 12, 2012 to validate all the payments made.

We recommended and management agreed to consider the following courses of action: 

Fill-up the vacant positions for more effective administration of the offices requiring their services;

Instruct the HRMO to observe strictly the pertinent CSC Rules on Designation;

Direct department heads/supervisors to refrain from authorizing and sending job order employees to trainings/seminars to avoid incurrence of unnecessary expenses; and

In inevitable cases when the nature of work of the job order personnel require them to travel, make sure that the same is stipulated in their individual contracts to be entitled to the payment/reimbursement of expenses provided under E.O. No. 77 dated March 15, 2019.

We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following courses of action:

Prepare the Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) to be submitted to the BAC Secretariat for consolidation and incorporation in the Annual Procurement Plan (APP); 

Practice bulk procurement in order to avail the most advantageous prices that the suppliers can offer; 

Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly adhere to the provisions of R.A. Nos. 9184 and 9502 also known as the Universally Accessible Cheaper and Quality Medicines Act of 2008 and Rule No. 36 of its IRR to ascertain that the procured drugs and medicines are of good quality, essential to the people and within the Philippine National Drug Formulary (PNDF);

Document properly all inventory issuances, including medicines given as assistance to the constituents; and

Request for the replacement of invalid official receipts issued by the suppliers of drugs and medicines.

We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following courses of action:

Require the LDRRM Officer to (i) monitor and evaluate the utilization of the LDRRMF based on the programs, projects, and activities listed in the LDRRMFIP to ensure the full implementation of planned activities; 



(ii) specify clearly in the plan the performance indicators and the schedule or period of project implementation to avoid delay in the project execution; 



(iii) incorporate GAD-related PPAs in the plan to ensure that disaster risk reduction measures are gender responsive; 



(iv) prepare the Report on the Utilization of LDRRMF to be certified correct by the Municipal Accountant and submitted to the Audit Team on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; 



(v) plan for the inclusion/integration of activities to be funded from the unexpended balances of the LDRRMF into the LDRRMFIP to rationalize the use of the Special Trust Fund; and 



(vi) apply for fidelity bond as the accountable officer for government-owned DRRM properties;



Initiate the creation of three positions for DRRM staff and the eventual hiring of such mandatory positions for the LDRRM Office in compliance with NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC JMC No. 2014-1; and

Make a representation from the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) for the authority to open and maintain a separate bank account with an Authorized Government Depository Bank (AGDB) to secure the Special Trust Fund from co-mingling with the regular Trust Fund.

We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following courses of action:

Direct the GFPS to fully implement the GAD PPAs and monitor their implementation to ensure that optimum benefits are derived by its constituents;



Direct the GFPS and GAD key personnel to undergo capacity building programs and trainings on gender and development to enhance their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender-responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD-related tools, among others;

Facilitate the establishment of the GAD M&E system as required by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 dated July 18, 2013 to help and assist the concerned officials in the proper monitoring of the implementation of GAD policies and PPAs and the evaluation of the effectiveness of the same;

Instruct the MPDC to facilitate the gathering of data/information needed for the creation of a well-established GAD database to have an accurate and reliable basis in the planning and programming of PPAs as well as in the policy formulation in order to properly address the existing and emerging GAD issues and concerns; and

Prioritize measures on the development and passage of a GAD Code pursuant to the provisions of PCW Memorandum Circular No. 2009-1 dated September 16, 2009, R.A. No. 9710 and PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 dated July 18, 2013 to provide the legal backbone in the proper implementation of GAD.

We recommended that management require the: 

Municipal Accountant to (1) draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) taking up the (i) adjustment of the accumulated depreciation of the Road Networks and Motor Vehicles accounts; and (ii) dropping of obsolete properties from the books upon disposal; and 

(2) update the PPELC for all property accounts to support the recorded balances of PPE;



GSO/Property Custodian to (i) report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) duly signed by the Head of Accounting Unit, Inspector/Appraisal Committee and approved by Head of Agency or authorized representative; (ii) submit the approved IIRUP to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition; and (iii) maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE;



Disposal Committee to immediately dispose all unserviceable and unusable office/other supplies and equipment using the appropriate mode of disposal, as determined and recommended by the Committee, to avoid further deterioration, earn income from the sale thereof, if warranted, and make use of the storage spaces occupied by these items; and

ensure that all its insurable properties are adequately covered by insurance with the GSIS to obtain maximum protection of the interest of the government and contribute to the revenue collection efforts of the National Government as well.

We recommended that management direct/instruct: 

the Municipal Accountant to (i) transfer the financial assistance from various NGAs and trust collections from the General Fund to the Trust Fund books in accordance with existing accounting policy;


 (ii) transfer the unutilized PDAF balance to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund;


 (iii) coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for the return of unused funds to the source agencies (SAs) or to the National Treasury, as the case may be; 

(iv) scrutinize the completeness of supporting documents of claims before releasing the same for payment and prior to the recording of the transactions in the books of accounts; and (v) record the procurement of assets in the Trust Fund books upon purchase and transfer the same after project completion to the General Fund books;



the Municipal Treasurer to draw a check for the remittance of unutilized amount of all completed projects and the remittance of ante mortem fees; and

the BAC and TWG to adhere to the documentary requirements in all stages of the bidding processes.

We reiterate our recommendation that management undertake the following measures:

Require the Municipal Treasurer to (i) strictly adhere to the regulations requiring the deposit of collections daily and intact; 


(ii) ensure that the balances reflected in the cashbooks correspond to the actual cash in vault per fund; and



(iii) ensure that the entries in the cashbooks are complete and accurate;

Refrain from using collections for emergency purchases and unapproved disbursements for more efficient and effective financial management; 

Prevent officials and employees from drawing vales or borrowing money from the collections of the Municipal Treasurer to forestall the recurrence of cash shortage; 
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile entries in the cashbook and accounting ledgers at least on a quarterly basis; and

Evaluate controls over the handling of cash to ensure proper accounting and adequate safeguard over government funds.

We recommended that management advice the:

Local School Board to (i) improve the utilization rate of the SEF and implement programs and projects, especially the improvements of school buildings and classrooms to ensure the provision of facilities conducive for learning; and (ii) prepare an Annual Procurement Plan for all the repairs of school buildings and facilities to support procurement of project materials and/or services as stated in the SEF budget; 

Municipal Accountant to (i) scrutinize the completeness of supporting documents of claims before releasing the same for payment; and (ii) immediately transmit the unsubmitted disbursement vouchers and supporting documents for SEF transactions for December 2018; 



Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to (i) refrain from resorting to alternative modes of procurement unless the circumstances warrant the adoption thereof; and
 (ii) submit written explanation for the splitting of requisitions/contracts noted during the audit; and

Municipal Engineer to submit complete documentation on the payment of labor for the repairs of school buildings and facilities.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Reorganize promptly/ timely the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board (MSWMB) to ensure that the Organization is capable on developing and adopting measures to observe the basic environmental regulations and to effectively implement the Municipality’s solid waste management programs, projects, and activities as planned;

Instruct the concerned officials to (i) strictly enforce the “No Segregation, No Collection Policy”; 



(ii) discontinue the practice of incinerating solid waste in the MRF;



 (iii) relocate the two shredders to a safe storage/warehouse in the MRF to maximize its use and to avoid further damage on the equipment; 



(iv) maximize the use of its MRF Office; and



 (v) abide strictly with the project schedule to ensure the full implementation of all the solid waste management priority projects targeted during the year for the benefit of the Municipality and the constituents in general;



Take appropriate action to expedite the necessary improvement on the Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) of the Municipality to make it operational; and



Pursue the establishment of a functional Sanitary Landfill.

We recommended that management (a) adhere to the required composition of the GAD Focal Point System and the creation of GFPS Technical Working Group (TWG) to institutionalize gender mainstreaming; 

(b) gather GAD information such as gender statistics and sex-disaggregated data to serve as inputs for planning, budgeting, programming and policy formulation for the setting up and maintenance of GAD database; 

(c) prioritize measures on the development and passage of a GAD Code; 



(d) ensure the timely submission of GAD Plan and Budget to the DILG and PPDO; 



(e) create a Monitoring and Evaluation Team to take responsibility of assessing the status of PPAs in relation to the plan and existing GAD policy; and 
(f) submit updated GAD Plan and Budget and GAD Accomplishment and Utilization Report to provide basis of measuring the performance of the LGU in terms of all the requirements of the PCW-DILG-DBM and NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 dated July 18, 2013.

General Services Officer to (i) maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE; (ii) perform test for the impairment of PPE at least annually, as required in PPSAS 21, and submit a report thereto, if any, to the Municipal Accountant for recording purposes; (iii) report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the IIRUP duly signed by the Head of the Accounting Unit and Inspector/Appraisal Committee, and approved by the Head of Agency or authorized representative; (iv) submit the approved IIRUP to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition; and (v) facilitate the transfer of the certificate of title over the acquired lots in favor of the Municipal Government to warrant the LGU’s absolute and clear ownership;

Municipal Accountant to (i) update the PPELC for all property accounts to support the recorded balances of PPE; (ii) recognize impairment losses, if any, in the books of accounts; (iii) adjust the books of accounts to recognize the cost of remaining supplies/materials held for distribution and record as expenses the cost of the distributed supplies/materials; (iv) drop the obsolete properties from the books upon disposal; (v) draw the appropriate journal entries to recognize the completed projects in the books of accounts as PPE and the related depreciation; (vi) reconcile the accounting office records with the Municipal Engineer based on the actual condition of the infrastructure projects; and (vii) adjust the books of accounts to recognize the cost of distributed water pumps acquired on CYs 2015 and 2016;

Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to (i) continue joint efforts to substantiate with valid documents the reconciliation of PPEs submitted; and (ii) continually strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the accounting records and actual inventory results; 
Disposal Committee to immediately dispose all unserviceable and unusable office/other supplies and equipment using the appropriate mode of disposal, as determined and recommended by the Committee, to avoid further deterioration, earn income from the sale thereof, if warranted, and make use of the storage spaces occupied by these items;

Municipal Engineer closely coordinate with offices concerned and report the status of infrastructure projects to the Accounting Department, particularly the completed projects that were duly inspected and accepted by management for the proper adjustment of the CIP accounts to the proper PPE accounts; and 

Municipal officials and employees who were accountable for the death/loss of the properties issued to them to prepare and submit Request for Relief from Accountability duly supported with the required documents enumerated under Section 499 of GAAM, Volume I and an explanation or justification for the submission thereof beyond the thirty-day prescription period.

