11.19	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Reorganize promptly/timely the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board (MSWMB) to ensure that the Organization is capable on developing and adopting measures to observe the basic environmental regulations and to effectively implement the Municipality’s solid waste management programs, projects, and activities as planned;
Instruct the concerned officials to (i) strictly enforce the “No Segregation, No Collection Policy”; (ii) discontinue the practice of incinerating solid waste in the MRF; (iii) relocate the two shredders to a safe storage/warehouse in the MRF to maximize its use and to avoid further damage on the equipment; (iv) maximize the use of its MRF Office; and (v) abide strictly with the project schedule to ensure the full implementation of all the solid waste management priority projects targeted during the year for the benefit of the Municipality and the constituents in general;
Take appropriate action to expedite the necessary improvement on the Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) of the Municipality to make it operational; and
Pursue the establishment of a functional Sanitary Landfill.

Require the Municipal Treasurer to (i) strictly adhere to the regulations requiring the deposit of collections daily and intact; (ii) ensure that the balances reflected in the cashbooks correspond to the actual cash in vault by fund; (iii) immediately restitute in full the remaining amount of cash shortage of ₱175,721.74; in case of non-restitution, consider the automatic relief of the accountable officer from cashiering function and the filing of administrative case against her; and (iv) ensure that entries in the cashbooks are complete and accurate to avoid incurrence of similar irregularity in the future;

Refrain from using collections for emergency purchases and unapproved disbursements for more efficient and effective financial management; 

Stop the practice of allowing officials and employees to borrow money from the collections of the Municipal Treasurer to avoid the recurrence of cash shortage; 

Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile entries in the cashbook and accounting ledgers at least on a quarterly basis; and

Evaluate controls over the handling of cash to ensure that government funds are properly accounted for and adequately safeguarded.

Require the LDRRMO to (i) regularly monitor the implementation of projects out of the Fund to maximize the utilization of the LDRRMF and to avoid absorption of PPAs which are more appropriately chargeable against the General Fund; and (ii) prepare the Report on the Utilization of DRRMF to be certified correct by the Municipal Accountant and submitted to the Audit Team on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; 

Properly plan for the inclusion/integration of activities to be funded from the unexpended balances of the LDRRMF into the Local Disaster and Risk Reduction Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) to rationalize the use of the Special Trust Fund;

Make representation from the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) for the authority to open and maintain a separate bank account with an Authorized Government Depository Bank (AGDB) to secure the Special Trust Fund from co-mingling with the regular Trust Fund; and

Monitor, secure, and preserve all the properties, equipment, supplies and materials procured under LDRRMF in a clean and properly arranged storeroom.

exercise strong political will and intensify campaign calling for active participation of all barangay officials to support further the solid waste management program of the government and provide continuous education to their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes to resolve the issue on waste segregation at source;

prioritize and provide adequate funding for the construction of functional MRF;


expedite the submission of the revised ten-year SWM Plan for approval of the National Solid Waste Management Commission (NSWMC);


secure proper storage/warehouse for the multi-purpose shredder and follow up the replacement of its battery from the supplier to make the equipment operational; and 


adopt clear-cut or concrete measures to promote and ensure a more viable and effective implementation of the solid waste management program of the Municipality.

Strive to implement all projects, programs and activities identified under the Bottom-up Budgeting (BuB) and cope with the timetable to ensure the full enjoyment of benefits that could be derived therefrom by the constituents of the Municipality;
Cause the proper liquidation of the fund transfers and return all excess funds to the source agencies (SAs) or National Treasury, as the case may be; and


Require the Municipal Accountant to submit immediately the unsubmitted disbursements and scrutinize the completeness of supporting documents of claims before releasing the same for payment and prior to the recording of the transactions in the books of accounts.

review the organizational structure and staffing requirement of the Municipality to determine the appropriate manpower complement for their programs/activities/projects;

instruct job order, honorarium-based personnel and consultant to submit quantifiable/comprehensive accomplishment reports; 

refrain from authorizing and sending job order employees to trainings/seminars to avoid incurrence of unnecessary expenses; and

consider the desired expertise, not available among the regular staff, in hiring a consultant and see to it that only those who possess expertise in their field of assignment and whose services are very necessary will be hired as required by laws, rules and regulations.

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to (i) exert effort to intensify the collections by undertaking effective revenue collection strategies such as periodic sending of notice of delinquency and tax bill by personal or mail service and coordination with barangay officials and national and local offices that have access to the addresses of delinquent taxpayers; and (ii) avail of all legal and administrative remedies allowed under R.A. No. 7160;


enforce the terms and conditions stipulated in the contract of lease relative to the period and mode of payment for rental of market stalls, imposition of surcharge/s for late and non-payment of lease to encourage space holders to promptly settle their accounts and avoid possible cancellation of their contract; and

amend and include provisions on the Contract of Lease that will clearly specify the application of advance monthly rental for unpaid rent, and the corresponding penalties and legal actions to be imposed for violating any provisions of the Lease Contract.

