General Services Officer to (i) maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE; (ii) perform test for the impairment of PPE at least annually, as required in PPSAS 21, and submit a report thereto, if any, to the Municipal Accountant for recording purposes; (iii) report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the IIRUP duly signed by the Head of the Accounting Unit and Inspector/Appraisal Committee, and approved by the Head of Agency or authorized representative; (iv) submit the approved IIRUP to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition; and (v) facilitate the transfer of the certificate of title over the acquired lots in favor of the Municipal Government to warrant the LGU’s absolute and clear ownership;
Municipal Accountant to (i) update the PPELC for all property accounts to support the recorded balances of PPE; (ii) recognize impairment losses, if any, in the books of accounts; (iii) adjust the books of accounts to recognize the cost of remaining supplies/materials held for distribution and record as expenses the cost of the distributed supplies/materials; (iv) drop the obsolete properties from the books upon disposal; (v) draw the appropriate journal entries to recognize the completed projects in the books of accounts as PPE and the related depreciation; (vi) reconcile the accounting office records with the Municipal Engineer based on the actual condition of the infrastructure projects; and (vii) adjust the books of accounts to recognize the cost of distributed water pumps acquired on CYs 2015 and 2016;
Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to (i) continue joint efforts to substantiate with valid documents the reconciliation of PPEs submitted; and (ii) continually strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the accounting records and actual inventory results;
Disposal Committee to immediately dispose all unserviceable and unusable office/other supplies and equipment using the appropriate mode of disposal, as determined and recommended by the Committee, to avoid further deterioration, earn income from the sale thereof, if warranted, and make use of the storage spaces occupied by these items;
Municipal Engineer closely coordinate with offices concerned and report the status of infrastructure projects to the Accounting Department, particularly the completed projects that were duly inspected and accepted by management for the proper adjustment of the CIP accounts to the proper PPE accounts; and
Municipal officials and employees who were accountable for the death/loss of the properties issued to them to prepare and submit Request for Relief from Accountability duly supported with the required documents enumerated under Section 499 of GAAM, Volume I and an explanation or justification for the submission thereof beyond the thirty-day prescription period.

We recommended that management undertake the following measures:
Require the Municipal Treasurer to (i) strictly adhere to the regulations requiring the deposit of collections daily and intact; (ii) ensure that the balances reflected in the cashbooks correspond to the actual cash in vault by fund; (iii) immediately restitute in full the remaining amount of cash shortage of ₱175,721.74; in case of non-restitution, consider the automatic relief of the accountable officer from cashiering function and the filing of administrative case against her; and (iv) ensure that entries in the cashbooks are complete and accurate to avoid incurrence of similar irregularity in the future;
Refrain from using collections for emergency purchases and unapproved disbursements for more efficient and effective financial management;
Stop the practice of allowing officials and employees to borrow money from the collections of the Municipal Treasurer to avoid the recurrence of cash shortage;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile entries in the cashbook and accounting ledgers at least on a quarterly basis; and
Evaluate controls over the handling of cash to ensure that government funds are properly accounted for and adequately safeguarded.
As of February 28, 2018, the Municipal Treasurer restituted the full amount of cash shortage of ₱175,721.74 and submitted the schedule of collections and deposits for the period February 15-28, 2018, copies of deposit slips and snapshots as proofs of her restitution. Likewise, a written explanation was rendered by the AO stating that the cash shortage was due to cash advances of some employees who were facing financial problems. She assured the Audit Team that she will implement necessary measures to avoid recurrence of similar irregularity. Management agreed to implement the other audit recommendations.

We recommended and management agreed to undertake the following measures:
Require the LDRRMO to (i) regularly monitor the implementation of projects out of the Fund to maximize the utilization of the LDRRMF and to avoid absorption of PPAs which are more appropriately chargeable against the General Fund; and (ii) prepare the Report on the Utilization of DRRMF to be certified correct by the Municipal Accountant and submitted to the Audit Team on or before the 15th day after the end of each month;
Properly plan for the inclusion/integration of activities to be funded from the unexpended balances of the LDRRMF into the Local Disaster and Risk Reduction Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) to rationalize the use of the Special Trust Fund;
Make representation from the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) for the authority to open and maintain a separate bank account with an Authorized Government Depository Bank (AGDB) to secure the Special Trust Fund from co-mingling with the regular Trust Fund; and
Monitor, secure, and preserve all the properties, equipment, supplies and materials procured under LDRRMF in a clean and properly arranged storeroom.
During the exit conference, management stated that the utilization of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF will be prioritized; programs such as purchase of construction and heavy equipment to be funded from the prior years’ unexpended balance will be included in the LDRRMIF. Regarding the proper safekeeping of procured properties under LDRRMF, management assured the Audit Team that all disaster rescue equipment and supplies will be transferred to the evacuation facility once completed. Management committed to implement the other audit recommendations of the Audit Team.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
exercise strong political will and intensify campaign calling for active participation of all barangay officials to support further the solid waste management program of the government and provide continuous education to their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes to resolve the issue on waste segregation at source;
prioritize and provide adequate funding for the construction of functional MRF;
expedite the submission of the revised ten-year SWM Plan for approval of the National Solid Waste Management Commission (NSWMC);
secure proper storage/warehouse for the multi-purpose shredder and follow up the replacement of its battery from the supplier to make the equipment operational; and
adopt clear-cut or concrete measures to promote and ensure a more viable and effective implementation of the solid waste management program of the Municipality.
During the exit conference, the Municipal Planning and Development Officer commented that the revised 10-year SMW Plan was already submitted to EMB for review and the battery of the shredder was already replaced by the supplier. The Municipal Mayor also added that the tarpaulins containing the information regarding the proper waste segregation will be distributed to all barangays. Management assured us of the compliance to the other audit recommendations to ensure protection of public health and environment.

We recommended that management:
review the organizational structure and staffing requirement of the Municipality to determine the appropriate manpower complement for their programs/activities/projects;
instruct job order, honorarium-based personnel and consultant to submit quantifiable/comprehensive accomplishment reports;
refrain from authorizing and sending job order employees to trainings/seminars to avoid incurrence of unnecessary expenses; and
consider the desired expertise, not available among the regular staff, in hiring a consultant and see to it that only those who possess expertise in their field of assignment and whose services are very necessary will be hired as required by laws, rules and regulations.
During the exit conference, management stated that the assessment of their organizational structure and staffing pattern is ongoing, vacant positions will be filled up, and unnecessary positions will be abolished. Management agreed to comply with the other audit recommendations of the Audit Team.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive: 

conduct training with the participation of all barangays relative to the segregation, re-use, recycle and composting of waste as starting point of implementation of the 10-year solid waste management plan;

pursue the construction of MRF to ensure the efficient management of solid waste generated within its jurisdiction;

adopt measures to promote and ensure the viability and effective implementation of the solid waste management program of the respective component barangays and municipality; and



monitor the implementation of R.A. No. 9003 in consonance with the Solid Waste Management Plan and evaluate the same as to its effectiveness.

We recommended that management:

consider the desired expertise, not available among the regular staff in hiring consultants and see to it that only those who possess expertise in their field of assignment and whose services are very necessary will be hired as required by laws, rules and regulations;

submit to COA copies of agreement forms and other documents forming part thereof within the reglementary period of five days from execution thereof;



instruct consultants to submit quantified/ comprehensive accomplishment reports which must be signed by them and noted by the concerned department heads; and

stop the payment of communication allowances to consultant to prevent audit disallowance.

We recommended that the management require the:
General Services Officer to (i) maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE; (ii) facilitate the transfer of the certificate of title over the acquired lots in favor of the Municipal Government to warrant the LGU’s absolute and clear ownership; and (iii) report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the IIRUP, duly signed by the Head of Accounting Unit, Inspector/Appraisal Committee and approved by the Head of Agency or authorized representative and submit to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition;
Municipal Accountant to (i) update the PPELC for all property accounts to support the recorded balances of PPE; and (ii) drop the obsolete properties from the books upon disposal;
Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to (i) continue joint efforts towards the reconciliation of the balances per books with that of the inventory report; and (ii) strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting and actual inventory results; and
Disposal Committee to immediately dispose all unserviceable and unusable office/other supplies and equipment using appropriate mode of disposal, as determined and recommended by the Committee, to avoid further deterioration, earn income from the sale thereof, if warranted, and make use of the storage spaces occupied by these items.

We recommended that the management undertake the following measures:
Require the BAC to (i) strictly comply with the procedures prescribed by R.A. No. 9184 on government procurement; (ii) submit other required documents to support the procurement of rescue vehicle such as copy of minutes of pre-bid conference and printout copies of the posting in PhilGEPS of the advertisement, Notice of Award, Notice to Proceed and Contract of Award; and (iii) submit a copy of all perfected contracts and all the documents forming part thereof within five working days from the execution of the same regardless of the amount;
Instruct the GSO Officer to submit the distribution list showing the names of actual recipients and their proof of receipt of raincoats and rain boots distributed for validation purposes;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) record as inventories small items purchased for disaster response and rescue activities, which do not qualify under the equipment classification; (ii) draw a JEV to record the unpaid procured items amounting to ₱104,800.00 to correctly state the balances of the affected assets and payable accounts in the financial statements; and (iii) henceforth, scrutinize the completeness of supporting documents of disbursements before releasing the same for payment; and
Direct the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer to (i) prepare the Report on the Utilization of DRRMF to be certified correct by the Municipal Accountant and submitted to the Audit Team on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; and (ii) regularly monitor the status and actual implementation of the projects financed out of the fund to avoid absorption of PPAs which are more appropriately chargeable against the General Fund.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support further the solid waste management program of the government by continuously educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes;
prioritize and provide adequate funding for the construction of functional MRF;
facilitate the transfer of the certificate of title over the acquired lot in favor of the Municipal Government to warrant the LGU’s absolute and clear ownership upon lifting of DENR suspension of acceptance and processing of public land applications;
expedite the revision of the ten-year SWM Plan for approval of the National Solid Waste Management Commission (NSWMC); and
adopt measures to promote and ensure the viability and effective implementation of the solid waste management program of the Municipality.

We recommended that the management:
Ensure the full implementation of all the priority projects targeted for the year for the benefit of the Municipality and the constituents in general;
Refrain from charging non-investment and non-capital expenditures to the 20% Development Fund, instead these expenditures must be properly charged to the General Fund Proper;
Submit an explanation for the discrepancies noted on the wages reported to have been paid to laborers during the conduct of coastal clean-up to enable the Audit Team to render an appropriate audit action; and
Advise the Municipal Accountant to review thoroughly all disbursement claims, including payrolls, for authenticity and validity in order to safeguard public funds from unscrupulous acts committed either by the payees themselves or those responsible for certifying/approving such claims.

We recommended that the management:
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to (i) take responsibility for the distribution and actual service of the notice of tax delinquency to the delinquent taxpayers; (ii) exert effort to intensify the collections by undertaking effective revenue collection strategies such as periodic sending of notice of delinquency and tax bill by personal or mail service and coordination with barangay officials and national and local offices that have access to the addresses of delinquent taxpayers; and (iii) avail of all legal and administrative remedies allowed under R.A. No. 7160;
enforce the terms and conditions stipulated in the contract of lease relative to the period and mode of payment for rental of market stalls, imposition of surcharge/s for late and non-payment of lease to encourage space holders to promptly settle their accounts and avoid possible cancellation of their contract.  Strict implementation of the provisions would also benefit management from an increased collection of rental from market stalls;
amend and include provisions on the Contract of Lease that will clearly specify the application of advance monthly rental for unpaid rent, the corresponding penalties and legal actions to be imposed for violating any provisions of the Lease Contract; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the rental receivables from the unpaid space rentals to ensure accuracy and reliability of the Agency’s Financial Statements.

We reiterated our recommendation that management: 

require the members of the BAC and Municipal Engineer to observe strictly the provisions of the RIRR of RA No. 9184 in every procurement process;

ensure the widest dissemination of procurement-related notices, strictly adhere to the advertising and posting requirements;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to diligently assure, check and scrutinize with due care the  completeness of the supporting documents  before payment is effected. Submit the eligibility checklist using the non- discretionary “pass/fail” criteria, bid evaluation report and post-qualification report of the above mentioned contracts for validity, legality and propriety of the transactions;

require the Municipal Engineer to submit documents evidencing monitoring, inspection and completion of the projects implemented by administration and provide certificate of project completion, certification that the municipality had a track record of having completed, or supervised a project similar to and with a cost of at least fifty percent of the projects at hand and own the tools and construction equipment to be used or have access to such tools and equipment owned by other government agencies to substantiate the effective and efficient implementation of the same; and

direct the BAC to immediately submit copies of perfected contracts, purchase order and supporting documents `within five days from  its execution in consonance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009.
